otivate acts to redress the situation, as displayed in the Black Lives Matter and climate change movements. This volume brings together perspectives from political science and philosophy to shed new light on the political faces of negative emotions. Engaging with real-world political events from Europe, the US and Africa, contributors critically evaluate much-discussed emotions, such as anger and fear, but also less prominent ones, such as frustration and discomfort.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aEmotionsxPolitical aspects. 0aEmotionsxSocial aspects. 0aNegativismxPolitical aspects. 0aNegativismxSocial aspects. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / World / General.2bisacsh1 aAdkins, Karen, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAndreasen, Søren Mosgaard, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCarman, Mary, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aClaeys, Martha, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDavies, William, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDegerman, Dan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDegerman, Dan, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aKalm, Sara, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLeiviskä, Anniina, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLeser, Julia, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMansikka, Jan-Erik, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMeeuwisse, Anna, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMunch-Jurisic, Ditte Marie, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPyy, Iida, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabular